title: For Sale:  9mm Pistol, Hungarian FEG P9RK
postcontent:
This beautiful 9 mm pistol is in like-new condition.  It is not a Hi Power, but it looks like one.  This FEG P9RK double-action semi-automatic pistol comes with an extra 14 round magazine, excellent factory walnut grips, and a secure carrying case, all for $350.  It would make a perfect duty pistol, or a protective house gun.

Here is a little history on the P9RK pistol:

The FEG P9RK is the short-barrel version of the P9R pistol. Both guns are made in Hungary by the FEGARMY Arms factory. The P9RK uses the modified P9 frame and action, with a Smith & Wesson double-action trigger system. 

The P9RK is a short recoil operated, locked breech pistol. The barrel is operated using a Browning cam system, and is locked to the slide by three locking lugs on the top of the barrel, which fit into mated recesses on the inside of the slide, just ahead of the ejection port. Frame and slide are made from carbon steel and have a blued finish. The Double Action trigger system with external hammer has a slide-mounted safety lever, which also works as a de-cocker when safety is engaged. The front sight is permanently fixed to the slide, while rear sight is dovetailed. 

The attached pictures do not do justice to the pistol.  The finish is bright blue and the grips are perfect.  You must see this pistol in person to fully appreciate it.  Contact me to arrange a time and meeting place.

title: For Sale:  Browning 12 GA. Auto 5 28 Barrel BELGIUM MADE SHOTGUN
postcontent:
The Browning Automatic 5, most often Auto-5 or simply A-5, is a recoil-operated semi-automatic shotgun designed by John Browning. It was the first successful semi-automatic shotgun designed and remained in production until 1998. The name of the shotgun designates that it is an autoloader with a capacity of five shots, four in the magazine and one in the chamber. (light use, normal wear)

The Browning Auto-5 is a long-recoil operated semi-automatic shotgun. Shells are stored in a tubular magazine under the barrel. When a chambered shell is fired, the barrel and bolt recoil together (for a distance greater than the shell length) and recock the hammer. As the barrel returns forward to its initial position the bolt remains behind and thus the spent shell is ejected. Then the bolt returns forward and feeds another shell from the magazine into the action. This type of long recoil action was the first of its kind and patented in 1900 by John Browning.

To load the weapon, shells are fed into the bottom of the action, where they are pushed into the tubular magazine. Most A-5s have removable plugs in the magazine which prevent more than 3 shells from being loaded (two in the magazine, plus one in the chamber) to comply with U.S. Federal migratory waterfowl laws, as well as some state hunting regulations. With the plug removed, the total capacity is 5 rounds. If the chamber is open (the operating handle is drawn back) the first shell loaded into the magazine tube will go directly into the chamber. The bolt then closes, and all further shells fed into the gun go into the magazine.

i have three optics that i have no use for anymore.  first is a gamo 4x32 .22 special.  comes with rings and covers, alum. turret covers with 1/4" per click at 100yds turrets.  rubberized coating for added protection.  optic is clear and holds its zero.  the reticle is a "fine duplex".  over all a great optic. 

second is a bsa 3-9x40 DeerHunter.  all adjustment points are checkered for easy adjustment with or with out gloves.  turrets are 1/4" aat 100yds, and alum. caps as well.  comes with rings and covers.  turrets are zero adjustable via allen set screws.  meaning that you can zero the optic to 100yds then set your turret back to zero with out changing the setting of your crosshairs.  the reticle is a "fine duplex"  with a center "bullseyes" dot and a bullet drop compensator.  

the gamo was originally installed on a .22 rifle but never really used and found the rifle more fun with out it.  i think a total of maybe 100rds werre shot through the gun with the optic mounted.  since then it has just been takng up room in the safe.  

the bsa has never been mounted on anything.  i baught this as a replacement scope for a rifle but then ended up recieving a different scope from my wife as a gift.  it is brand new.  

i paid a totalof $250 for both scopes and spent about another $60 on rings and covers for them.  looking to make a straight trade.  make me an offer
